09:10.442 --> 09:16.953
Now, the word that you used here in Hebrew is one of the richest words in all of the Bible.

09:17.254 --> 09:22.723
In English, we have about 10 times more words in English than we do in Hebrew.

09:22.763 --> 09:24.466
So these Hebrew words are

09:24.546 --> 09:29.413
are just loaded with significance and rich with meaning, layer after layer.

09:29.493 --> 09:35.562
And so the word that's used here that can be translated as love is the Hebrew word chesed.

09:36.203 --> 09:37.585
Would you guys say that out loud with me?

09:37.926 --> 09:38.427
Chesed.

09:38.727 --> 09:42.993
If you need to clear your throat, it's a great word to pray and to put on your lips.

09:43.374 --> 09:51.506
It can really more literally be translated as like a loving kindness or a steadfast love or a commitment.

09:52.706 --> 10:00.637
John Golden Gay, who is an Old Testament scholar, he has a more elongated and elaborate definition of Hesse, and here is what he writes.

10:00.697 --> 10:21.106
He says that Hesse, the Old Testament uses this word to refer to an extraordinary act of generosity, allegiance, or grace, whereby someone pledges himself or herself to someone else when there is no prior relationship between them, and therefore no reason why the person should do so.

10:21.762 --> 10:23.003
That's how God pursues us.

10:23.865 --> 10:36.680
It can also refer to a similar extraordinary act that takes place when there is a relationship between people, but one party has let the other party down and therefore has no right to expect any faithfulness from the other.

10:37.501 --> 10:48.594
If that party that has been let down continues being faithful, she or he is showing the special kind of commitment or has it.

10:49.954 --> 10:53.518
So based on this definition, what does David hear the psalmist proclaiming?

